begin
reserve m for Nat;
reserve n for Nat;
theorem
Th28: (m > ( 0 ) implies ( n gcd m ) = ( m gcd ( n mod m ) ))
proof
set r = ( n mod m );
set x = ( n gcd m );
set y = ( m gcd r );
assume m > ( 0 );
then consider t being Nat such that A1: n = ( ( m * t ) + r ) and r < m by CKB2:def 1;
reconsider t as (Element of ( NAT )) by ORDINAL1:def 12;
A2: x divides n by CKB19:def 1;
A3: x divides m by CKB19:def 1;
then x divides r by A2,CKB16:1;
then A4: x divides y by A3,CKB19:def 1;
A5: y divides m by CKB19:def 1;
A6: y divides r by CKB19:def 1;
y divides ( m * t ) by A5,CKB14:1;
then y divides n by A1,A6,CKB13:1;
then y divides x by A5,CKB19:def 1;
hence thesis by A4,CKB10:1;
end;
